50|$|Charles' <b>disinheritance</b> {{received}} further legal sanction {{after he}} declared himself regent for Charles VI in rivalry to the regency declared by Henry V. The Dauphin {{was summoned to}} a lit-de justice (legal hearing) in 1420 on charges of lèse-majesté. When he failed to appear, a Parisian court in 1421 found Charles the Dauphin guilty of treason and sentenced him to <b>disinheritance</b> and banishment from the Kingdom of France, losing all privileges to land and titles.|$|E
