50|$|He was {{the second}} son of Sir Baldwin Mountfort of Coleshill-in-Arden, Warwickshire who he jointly succeeded with his brother Edmund after the <b>disinheritance</b> of their elder brother Baldwin. He was knighted in 1417.|$|E
50|$|His heir was {{a distant}} cousin, Prince Hermann of Saxe-Weimar-Eisenach, until his <b>disinheritance</b> in 1909. Hermann's younger brother {{subsequently}} served as heir presumptive to the Duchy of Saxe-Weimar-Eisenach until the birth of William Ernest's eldest son.|$|E
50|$|In 1763, {{when his}} father died, he disowned his son in his will, stating that he had married his mother only to legitimize him, and then {{proceeded}} to list {{a number of reasons}} justifying the <b>disinheritance.</b>|$|E
50|$|In {{orthodox}} Serer religion (an ethnoreligious faith), interfaith and interracial {{marriages are}} forbidden. Banishment and <b>disinheritance</b> may be levied against a Serer who disobeys the law, The Serer-Noon (a sub-group of the Serer people) adhere strongly to this teaching.|$|E
